<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="23" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Shell small (H = 1.5 mm, W = 2.9 mm), helicoid, depressed or triangular, wider than high. Color uniformly brown or purplish. Apex prominent; protoconch smooth or with dense mesh of granular reticulation. Teleoconch smoothish, but with uneven, oblique striatae. Spire slightly concave, sometimes scalariform. Body whorl keeled or rounded, often with a groove below suture. Shell umbilicate; umbilicus narrow to moderately narrow. Aperture oblique, rounded, with 0-5 apertural teeth; peristome thin, expanded.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="23" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="23">
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.842.33052" author="Pall-Gergely, B" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" pagination="67 - 83" refId="B10" refString="Pall-Gergely, B, Schilthuizen, M, Oerstan, A, Auffenberg, K, 2019. A review of Aulacospira Moellendorff, 1890 and Pseudostreptaxis Moellendorff, 1890 in the Philippines (Gastropoda, Pupilloidea, Hypselostomatidae). ZooKeys 842: 67 - 83, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.842.33052" title="A review of Aulacospira Moellendorff, 1890 and Pseudostreptaxis Moellendorff, 1890 in the Philippines (Gastropoda, Pupilloidea, Hypselostomatidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.842.33052" volume="842" year="2019">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Páll-Gergely">Pall-Gergely</normalizedToken>
et al. (2019)
</bibRefCitation>
suggested that Thai and Philippine 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moellendorff" authorityYear="1890" class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Aulacospira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aulacospira" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Aulacospira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may not be closely related due to their unusual distribution pattern and suggested that the similar shell shape of these snails may be due to convergence but more data are needed to support this hypothesis. However, we continue to use 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moellendorff" authorityYear="1890" class="Gastropoda" family="Gastrocoptidae" genus="Aulacospira" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aulacospira" order="Stylommatophora" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="23">Aulacospira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for Thai species following the description of this genus by 
<bibRefCitation author="Pilsbry, HA" journalOrPublisher="The Natural History Journal of Chulalongkorn University" pageId="0" pageNumber="23" refId="B15" refString="Pilsbry, HA, 1916-1918. Pulmonata, Pupillidae (Gastrocoptinae). Manual of Conchology, Second series: Pulmonata 24: i-xii, 1-380, pls 1-49." title="Pulmonata, Pupillidae (Gastrocoptinae). Manual of Conchology, Second series: Pulmonata 24: i-xii, 1 - 380, pls 1 - 49." year="1916 - 1918">Pilsbry (1916-1918)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
